description:
In rust/lichen-oscore/src/edhoc.rs, edhoc_kdf was changed from returning heapless::Vec directly to returning Result<heapless::Vec, EdhocError>. While this is correct, the refactor changed:

    // Before: Silent truncation on overflow
    okm.resize(length, 0).expect('length <= 32');
    hk.expand(&info, &mut okm).expect('length <= 255');
    okm

    // After: Returns error on overflow
    okm.resize(length, 0).expect('output Vec<u8, 32> fits any KDF output <= 32');
    hk.expand(&info, &mut okm).expect('requested length <= 32 is within HKDF-Expand limits');
    Ok(okm)

The expect() calls still exist, meaning the function can panic. For a crypto function, panics are generally undesirable. The Result return type suggests callers expect errors, but panics will bypass the Result.

Location: rust/lichen-oscore/src/edhoc.rs:163-174
Risk: Panic in crypto code path; callers think they handle errors but can still panic.
Fix: Remove expect() calls and propagate errors, or document when panics are impossible.
